Java allows for method overloading, unlike some other programming languages. This essentially means you can write this into your code:

```java
public void remove(String name, int population, 
			double area, String continent) {
	
	// your code goes here
	
}

// This will have a different method signature 
// and will allow you to use remove(&quot;Canada&quot;) 
// on its own.
public void remove(String name) {
	
	remove(name, 0, 0.0, &quot;&quot;);
	
}
```

Note that for this to work properly, we would have to assume that `.equals()` ignores the `population`, `area`, and `continent` fields. If it does use these fields, you would need a way to determine the fields programmatically, perhaps by using a country dictionary.

In case you **really** want to be able to create an instance of `Country` using only one parameter, you could overload its constructor:

    public class Country
    ...
        public Country(String name) {
            this(name, -1, -1, null);
        }
    ...


And then in your `remove()` method you could just do:

    public void remove(String name) {
        /* Make a new country object for removing */    
        Country removeCountry = new Country(name);
        ...

This is assuming that the `equals()` method of the `Country` class compares only its `name` field.

**Explanation**

In java, the same class can have multiple constructors with different parameters. This is called &quot;[constructor overloading][1]&quot;.

What `this(name, -1, -1, null)` does is that when you instantiate using this single-parameter constructor, it will in turn call the existing four-parameter constructor during instantiation, passing on its `name` argument.


